hook.real_world_problem:
Imagine building a `Pair` class that holds two values. Without generics, you'd write it with `Object`:

```java
class Pair {
    private Object first;
    private Object second;
    Pair(Object first, Object second) { this.first = first; this.second = second; }
    Object getFirst()  { return first; }
    Object getSecond() { return second; }
}

// Usage — looks fine until you run it:
Pair p = new Pair("Hyderabad", 42);
String city = (String) p.getFirst();   // cast required
Integer num  = (Integer) p.getFirst(); // ClassCastException at runtime!
```

Two problems:
1. You need casts everywhere — ugly and verbose
2. The compiler can't catch type errors — they crash at runtime

**With generics:**

```java
class Pair<A, B> {
    private final A first;
    private final B second;
    Pair(A first, B second) { this.first = first; this.second = second; }
    A getFirst()  { return first; }  // no cast needed
    B getSecond() { return second; } // no cast needed
}

// Usage:
Pair<String, Integer> p = new Pair<>("Hyderabad", 42);
String city   = p.getFirst();   // type safe — no cast
Integer num   = p.getSecond();  // type safe — no cast
// Integer wrong = p.getFirst(); // COMPILE ERROR — not Integer, it's String
```

The compiler now knows `first` is a `String` and `second` is an `Integer`. Wrong type usage → compile error, not runtime crash. This is what generics do: **move type errors from runtime to compile time**.

You've been using generic classes since Module 3 (`List<String>`, `Map<String, Integer>`). Today you learn how to BUILD them.

concept_explanation.why_generics:
**Why generics exist — the two problems they solve:**

**Problem 1: Without generics, containers use Object — dangerous casts**
```java
// Pre-Java 5 (before generics):
List names = new ArrayList();
names.add("Aisha");
names.add(42);  // accidentally added an int!
String name = (String) names.get(1);  // ClassCastException at runtime!
```

**Problem 2: No type safety — errors found at runtime, not compile time**

Both problems vanish with generics:
```java
// With generics:
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
names.add("Aisha");
names.add(42);  // COMPILE ERROR — must be String
String name = names.get(0);  // no cast needed — type is known
```

**The payoff**: bugs caught at compile time. Clean code without casts. Same class, any type.

concept_explanation.generic_class_syntax:
**Defining a generic class:**

```java
class ClassName<T> {
    // T is the type parameter — a placeholder for the actual type
    private T value;

    public ClassName(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    public T getValue() {
        return value;
    }
}
```

`<T>` after the class name is the **type parameter declaration**. `T` is a placeholder. When you create an instance, you provide the actual type:

```java
ClassName<String>  s = new ClassName<>("hello");  // T = String
ClassName<Integer> n = new ClassName<>(42);        // T = Integer
// The <> is the diamond operator — type inferred from declaration
```

**The type parameter `T` can be used:**
- As the type of a field: `private T value`
- As a parameter type: `void set(T value)`
- As a return type: `T get()`
- As a local variable type inside methods

**What `T` cannot be used for:**
- `new T()` — can't instantiate a type parameter
- `T[]` array creation — use List<T> instead
- `instanceof T` — type erasure (see below)

concept_explanation.multiple_type_parameters:
**Multiple type parameters:**

```java
class Pair<A, B> {
    private final A first;
    private final B second;

    public Pair(A first, B second) {
        this.first = first;
        this.second = second;
    }

    public A getFirst()  { return first; }
    public B getSecond() { return second; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "(" + first + ", " + second + ")";
    }

    // swap: returns Pair<B, A> — types are reversed!
    public Pair<B, A> swap() {
        return new Pair<>(second, first);
    }
}

// Usage:
Pair<String, Integer> p1 = new Pair<>("Hyderabad", 500032);
System.out.println(p1);           // (Hyderabad, 500032)
System.out.println(p1.swap());    // (500032, Hyderabad)

Pair<String, Boolean> p2 = new Pair<>("premium", true);
System.out.println(p2.getFirst() + " = " + p2.getSecond());
```

concept_explanation.generic_methods_on_generic_class:
**Methods on generic classes:**

```java
class Stack<T> {
    private List<T> elements = new ArrayList<>();

    public void push(T element) {
        elements.add(element);
    }

    public T pop() {
        if (isEmpty()) throw new NoSuchElementException("Stack is empty");
        return elements.remove(elements.size() - 1);
    }

    public T peek() {
        if (isEmpty()) throw new NoSuchElementException("Stack is empty");
        return elements.get(elements.size() - 1);
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() { return elements.isEmpty(); }
    public int size()        { return elements.size(); }

    public List<T> toList() {
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(elements);
    }
}

// Works for any type:
Stack<String> words = new Stack<>();
words.push("hello");
words.push("world");
System.out.println(words.pop());  // world

Stack<Integer> nums = new Stack<>();
nums.push(1); nums.push(2); nums.push(3);
System.out.println(nums.pop());   // 3
```

concept_explanation.raw_types:
**Raw types** — generics used without type parameter (old Java style):

```java
// Raw type — don't do this:
List rawList = new ArrayList();  // no type parameter
rawList.add("string");
rawList.add(42);  // no compile error — raw type accepts anything
String s = (String) rawList.get(1);  // ClassCastException!

// Generic type — correct:
List<String> typedList = new ArrayList<>();
typedList.add("string");
typedList.add(42);  // COMPILE ERROR — wrong type
```

Raw types exist for backwards compatibility with pre-Java 5 code. **Never use raw types in new code.** They lose all type safety benefits. Your IDE will warn you about them.

